observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the LCE agreed, through the Municipal Accountant, Budget Officer, and Treasurer, (a) to provide the following supporting documents for the grant of CNA incentive as identified in Section 2 of PSLMC Resolution No. 4 series of 2002, Item 4.0 of BC No. 2022-3 dated October 19, 2022, and Item 5.16 of COA Circular 2012-001 as follows:

specific cost-cutting measures as provided in the signed CNA between the union and management;
proof that the funds for the incentives were taken from savings from allowable MOOE allotments as a result of cost-saving measures;
Resolution signed by both parties, incorporating the guidelines/criteria for granting CNA Incentive;
Comparative statement of DBM-approved level of operating expenses and actual operating expenses;
Copy of CNA;
Certificate issued by the Head of the Agency on the total amount of encumbered savings generated from cost-cutting measures identified in the CNA, which resulted from the joint efforts of labor and management and systems/productivity/income improvement;
Proof that the planned PPAs have been implemented and completed in accordance with the targets for the year.
(b)  For the Municipal Accountant to ensure the propriety of granting CNA incentives by ensuring that relevant and complete documents supporting its grant are available before making payments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	create an inventory team to conduct physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and submit to COA;

b.	require the Accounting and Treasury Office to complete their property ledger cards and conduct periodic reconciliation thereof; 

c.	require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer, to conduct an inventory of all parcels of land owned by the Municipality, recover the proof of ownership and thereafter establish the correct balance of Land account;

d.	require the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the retrieval of records and supporting documents for the preparation of the Registry of Public Infrastructures, which is a supporting document to the journal entry voucher to be prepared in recording back to the appropriate asset account the public infrastructures transferred therein, and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted; and

e.	require the Municipal accountant to follow the guidelines for the depreciation of PPE.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

a.	Municipal Development Council to justify the procurement of consultancy services instead of requesting the technical assistance of HLRB and other NGAs concerned in land use in the updating of the CLUP of the Municipality;

b.	Bids and Awards Committee and Municipal Accountant to explain the deficiencies noted and submit the lacking documents stated above.

1.18	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
create an inventory team to conduct physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and submit to COA;
require the Accounting and Treasury Office to complete their property ledger cards and conduct periodic reconciliation thereof;
require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer, to conduct an inventory of all parcels of land owned by the Municipality, recover the proof of ownership and thereafter establish the correct balance of Land account;
require the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the retrieval of records and supporting documents for the preparation of the Registry of Public Infrastructures, which is a supporting document to the journal entry voucher to be prepared in recording back to the appropriate asset account the public infrastructures transferred therein, and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted; and
require the Municipal accountant to follow the guidelines for the depreciation of PPE.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 
(i)	Send written reminders/demand to the concerned accountable officers for the immediate settlement of their unliquidated cash advances by submitting the liquidation report and settlement documents to the Accounting Office and/or by returning the unexpended balance of the cash advance to the Municipal Treasurer; 
(ii)	discontinue the granting of additional cash advances to officers and employees who failed to settle their previous accountabilities; 
(iii)	discontinue the granting of claims for travel expenses of employees who are not regular personnel of the Municipality; and
(iv)	settle the difference of P38,998.00 between the records on cash advances and the GL account.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:
a.	the LSB to follow and perform the activities and preparation and approval of the SEF Budget with indicative timelines as prescribed by DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 dated January 19, 2017 or the Revised Guidelines on the Use of Special Education Fund (SEF); 
b.	the Bids and Awards Committee follow provisions of the IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of infrastructure projects and goods; 
c.	the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Report of SEF Utilization quarterly and annually using the prescribed form for submission to appropriate offices and ensure the completeness of supporting documents before effecting payments and before granting of additional cash advances; and
d.	the Bids and Awards Committee, the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant to justify the deficiencies or submit appropriate documents pertaining to paragraph 1.11.

We recommended that the Executive Committee and the Technical Working Group of GFPS:
Prioritize the formulation of the Municipality’s GAD Code to support the LGU’s efforts toward the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment pursuant to RA No. 9710 and JMC of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA;
Lead the preparation of GAD database in accordance with JMC No. 2013-001 to be able to come up with more gender-issue responsive programs, activities and projects;
Monitor properly the implementation of the GAD Plan and ensure that the GAD Activities were substantially completed;
Endeavor to capacitate themselves through attendance to GAD-related trainings for  more responsive planning; and
Assess the extent of compliance through a compliance checklist of the elements of the institutional mechanisms in place and intensify efforts on those areas that should be in place.
